Actually for Scala this already works fine:

``` scala
class LoggingAction @Inject()(injectedLogger) extends ActionBuilder[Request] {
  def invokeBlock[A](request: Request[A], block: (Request[A]) => Future[Result]) = {
    injectedLogger.info("Calling action")
    block(request)
  }
}
class DemoController @Inject()(loggingAction: LoggingAction) extends Controller {
}
```

The only problem is Java here since it actually uses annotations to do it.

Java is not a problem here since you can also inject components in your actions:

```java
public class MetricsAction extends Action<Metrics> {

    private final MetricsRegister metricsRegister;

    @Inject
    public MetricsAction(MetricsRegister metricsRegister) {
        this.metricsRegister = metricsRegister;
    }

    public CompletionStage<Result> call(Http.Context ctx) {
        // do your thing
    }
}
```
The annotations are used only to mark the actions/controllers, but the actual action composition already happens using Dependency Injection.

@gmethvin are we missing something here?
